    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "9e3b1edd3238cca0",
      "text": "Kronecker made his famous quote “God made the integers, all else is the work of man.” at a meeting in 1886 (from his obituary, 1823-1891, in Mathematische Annalen 43:1-25). It was recently publicized as the title of a book by Stephen Hawking, God Created the Integers: The mathematical breakthroughs that changed history (2007). The quote is associated with Kronecker’s belief that mathematics should address finite numbers and should avoid the irrational numbers, a position similar to that taken here with regard to real numbers. But there is no need to interject metaphysics, man created the rationals as well as the irrationals. Brian Smith (On the Origin of Objects, 1996, p.355) comments that Kronecker got it backwards. Metaphysics arises out of indefiniteness, the absence of boundaries, from which we then carve out the discrete numbers. Irving Stein (The Concept of Object as the Foundation of Physics, 1996, abstract) points to the first distinction: “Objects arise from restrictions on nonspace.”"
    },
