      "item": {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "id": "ef3f32c9f7f035a2",
        "text": "Objects are defined by their interactions rather than by their independent properties. Put colorfully, a hand is not five fingers, it is thirty-two relations between fingers. The uncountable constructions of our minds illustrate clearly the limitations of arithmetic. We cannot count thoughts, feelings, beliefs, the wind, a river, sunshine, frost, the internet, a conversation or the web of life. We can count peaks but not mountains, snowflakes but not snow, branches but not roots, heartbeats but not metabolism, airplanes but not clouds, notes but not music, words but not ideas. We cannot count things that change faster than our ability to assign numbers to them. We cannot count the discrete packets of data distributed over the internet because there are too many and they change too quickly. If we were to freeze the internet, or any physiological process, or any natural process, we might be able to count the static pieces that break off but we would be counting only the fragments of a dead thing, the living thing would have moved on to be something different. We cannot accurately say out loud the national debt (even if we could count the dollars) because by the time it was out of our mouths, the debt would have changed by a personal fortune."
